<HH> ============= Screen: Predict why punishment is not a function ========= </HH>

<IntakeGate id="fba2_predict_punishment" ready="@fba2_punishment_confidence.value">

  <!-- Front: predict before seeing the answer -->
  <Vertical>
    <Markdown>
## Predict: Why Not Punishment?

Annie mentioned that she asked AI why punishment isn't listed as a function of behavior. **Before reading the answer, write your own prediction.** Think about what "function" means and how it relates to reinforcement.
    </Markdown>

    <TextArea id="fba2_no_punishment_explanation" rows="3"
      placeholder="Why do you think punishment is not a function of behavior? Write your prediction..." />

    <Markdown>Once you've written your prediction, **select a confidence level below to see the real answer.** (You won't be able to change your prediction after selecting.)</Markdown>
    <ChoiceInput id="fba2_punishment_confidence">
      <Key value="very">Very confident — I'm sure about this</Key>
      <Key value="somewhat">Somewhat confident — I think so but I'm not sure</Key>
      <Key value="guess">Just guessing</Key>
    </ChoiceInput>
  </Vertical>

  <!-- Back: show prediction alongside the answer -->
  <Vertical>
    <Markdown>
## Your Prediction

{{text2markdown(@fba2_no_punishment_explanation.value)}}

---

## AI Response: Why Punishment Is Not a Function of Behavior

_Annie asked AI this question earlier. Here's what it said:_

> **Why isn't punishment listed as a function of behavior?**
>
> Great question! The four functions of behavior — **attention**, **escape**,
> **access to tangibles**, and **sensory** — all describe what *maintains*
> or *reinforces* a behavior. When we ask "What is the function of this
> behavior?", we're really asking: **"What is this behavior getting for the
> person?"**
>
> - If the behavior gets them **attention**, the function is attention.
> - If the behavior helps them **escape** something unpleasant, the function is escape.
> - If the behavior gets them **access** to something they want, the function is tangibles.
> - If the behavior itself **feels good**, the function is sensory.
>
> **Punishment**, by definition, *decreases* behavior — it doesn't maintain
> it. Since the function of behavior describes what keeps the behavior going
> (i.e., what reinforces it), punishment cannot be a function. The function
> always tells us what the person is **gaining** (positive reinforcement) or
> **avoiding** (negative reinforcement) through their behavior.
    </Markdown>
  </Vertical>

</IntakeGate>


<HH> ============= Screen: Function sorting ===================== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_function_sorting">

<Markdown>
## Practice: Identify the Function of Each Behavior

Answer **6 questions correctly in a row** to demonstrate mastery. Each scenario
describes a behavior with its antecedent and consequence. Identify which function
the behavior serves:

- **Escape** — behavior removes or delays something aversive
- **Attention** — behavior produces social attention (even negative attention)
- **Sensory** — behavior produces its own internal reinforcement
- **Access/Tangible** — behavior obtains a preferred item or activity

You need to get **6 correct in a row** to move on. If you get one wrong, your streak resets — correct your answer, then keep going.
</Markdown>

<MasteryBank id="fba2_function_mastery" goal="6" mode="shuffle" src="function-questions.auto.idlistpeg" />

</Vertical>


<HH> ============= Screen: Ask AI for ABC diagrams ============== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_ai_abc_diagrams">
<Markdown>
## Ask AI: The ABCs of Behavior

Ask AI to create a **flowchart diagram** showing the ABCs (Antecedent → Behavior → Consequence) for each of the four functions of behavior.
</Markdown>

<Collapsible id="fba2_abc_diagram_hint" title="Hint: Example prompt">
<Markdown>
Try a prompt like: "Create a flowchart showing the ABC pattern for each function of behavior — escape, attention, access/tangible, and sensory — with a classroom example for each."
</Markdown>
</Collapsible>

<TextArea id="fba2_ai_abc_prompt" rows="2" placeholder="Ask AI to create Mermaid ABC diagrams for each function of behavior..." />

<ActionButton id="fba2_ai_abc_btn" label="Ask AI">
<SetFieldAction id="fba2_ai_abc_trigger" target="fba2_ai_abc_placeholder" field="value" value="*Generating diagram — this may take up to a minute...*" />
<LLMAction id="fba2_ai_abc_action" target="fba2_ai_abc_response"><![CDATA[
If the following question is about the ABCs (Antecedent, Behavior, Consequence) model
in behavioral psychology and how it relates to the four functions of behavior
(attention, escape, access/tangibles, sensory), provide a brief explanation of each
ABC example in the diagram. For each function, describe the example and explain whether
it involves positive or negative reinforcement.

If the student's question is not relevant to ABCs or functions of behavior,
point that out and stop.
]]>
Student prompt: <Ref id="fba2_ref_abc_prompt" target="fba2_ai_abc_prompt" />
</LLMAction>
<LLMAction id="fba2_ai_abc_code_action" target="fba2_ai_abc_code"><![CDATA[
If the following question is about the ABCs (Antecedent, Behavior, Consequence) model
and functions of behavior, generate ONLY valid Mermaid flowchart code. No explanations,
no markdown, no code fences — output must start with "flowchart LR" and contain nothing
else besides valid Mermaid syntax.

Create a single diagram with four subgraphs, one per function of behavior. Each subgraph
shows an Antecedent, Behavior, and Consequence connected by arrows, using a concrete
classroom example. Follow this structure:

flowchart LR
  subgraph escape ["Escape — Negative Reinforcement"]
    E_A["Antecedent: ..."] --> E_B["Behavior: ..."] --> E_C["Consequence: ..."]
  end
  subgraph attention ["Attention — Positive Reinforcement"]
    A_A["Antecedent: ..."] --> A_B["Behavior: ..."] --> A_C["Consequence: ..."]
  end
  subgraph tangible ["Access/Tangible — Positive Reinforcement"]
    T_A["Antecedent: ..."] --> T_B["Behavior: ..."] --> T_C["Consequence: ..."]
  end
  subgraph sensory ["Sensory — Automatic Reinforcement"]
    S_A["Antecedent: ..."] --> S_B["Behavior: ..."] --> S_C["Consequence: ..."]
  end

Rules:
- Output ONLY mermaid code — no other text whatsoever
- Wrap all node labels in double quotes inside square brackets: E_A["label"]
- Use underscores in node names (E_A, not E-A)
- Keep each label under 50 characters
- Do NOT use bare colons, parentheses, or special characters outside the double quotes

If the question is not relevant, output only:
flowchart LR
  A["Please ask about ABCs and functions of behavior"]
]]>
Student prompt: <Ref id="fba2_ref_abc_code_prompt" target="fba2_ai_abc_prompt" />
</LLMAction>
</ActionButton>

<LLMFeedback id="fba2_ai_abc_response" render="markdown" when="@fba2_ai_abc_response.value" />

<Markdown id="fba2_ai_abc_placeholder" when="!@fba2_ai_abc_code.value">
*Your diagram will appear here once the AI finishes generating it. The text explanation will appear first; the diagram follows after and may take up to a minute. If it doesn't render correctly, click "Ask AI" again — the AI sometimes needs another attempt to get the diagram syntax right.*
</Markdown>
<Mermaid id="fba2_ai_abc_diagram" target="fba2_ai_abc_code" when="@fba2_ai_abc_code.value" />
<Collapsible id="fba2_mermaid_source" title="View diagram source code" when="@fba2_ai_abc_code.value">
